---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Curriculum Intelligence Dashboard"
  description="A Google Apps Script web app that turned scattered curriculum documents into a live analytics system tracking 216 courses and 849 units across three school divisions — deployed to 50+ leaders at AISC Chennai."
>
  <Nav />
  <main>

    <!-- HERO -->
    <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-navy via-teal-900 to-teal text-white py-16 md:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 md:px-8">
        <a href="/work" class="text-teal-200 text-sm hover:text-white transition-colors">← Back to all work</a>
        <span class="tag bg-white/10 text-white border border-white/20 mt-6 mb-5 inline-block">Flagship Project · Google Apps Script</span>
        <p class="text-amber text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">Chapter 4 · Become the institution's memory</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-5 leading-tight">Curriculum Intelligence Dashboard</h1>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-lg leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
          A curriculum analytics web app that made an entire school's curriculum visible, searchable,
          and actionable — and became the first onboarding resource 26 incoming teachers received before
          they ever arrived in Chennai.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- METRICS BAR -->
    <section class="bg-teal text-white py-8">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 md:px-8">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-6 text-center">
          {[
            { value: '216', label: 'Courses tracked' },
            { value: '849', label: 'Units · 81% complete' },
            { value: '50+', label: 'Leaders using it' },
            { value: '3', label: 'School divisions' },
          ].map(({ value, label }) => (
            <div>
              <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-amber">{value}</div>
              <div class="text-sm text-teal-100 mt-1">{label}</div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <article class="py-16 md:py-20 bg-white">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 md:px-8 space-y-14">

        <!-- OVERVIEW -->
        <div>
          <span class="tag mb-4">Overview</span>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">What it is</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              The Curriculum Intelligence Dashboard is a Google Apps Script web application that gives
              an entire IB World School a single, living view of its curriculum across Elementary, Middle,
              and High School. Instead of curriculum living in hundreds of disconnected documents, leaders
              get a navigable dashboard: a course Navigator, a Standards view with a Visible-for-Learning
              heatmap and gap analysis, a Head-of-Department view, a Gantt-style curriculum Calendar, and
              an AI tab for deeper queries.
            </p>
            <p>
              Underneath it sits the AISC Curriculum Documentation Tracker — a structured system tracking
              <strong class="text-navy">216 courses and 849 units</strong> across all three divisions,
              reaching <strong class="text-navy">81% school-wide completion</strong> by June 2026.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PROBLEM -->
        <div>
          <span class="tag mb-4">The Problem</span>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Curriculum nobody could see</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Like most schools, AISC's curriculum knowledge was real but invisible. It lived in
              individual planning documents, in teachers' heads, and in formats that varied by division
              and department. Leaders couldn't answer basic strategic questions — which standards are
              under-assessed, where are the gaps, how complete is our documentation — without weeks of
              manual auditing.
            </p>
            <p>
              When documentation isn't visible, it doesn't get used, it doesn't stay consistent, and it
              walks out the door every time a teacher leaves. The school needed institutional knowledge
              to become an asset rather than a liability.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- WHAT I BUILT -->
        <div>
          <span class="tag mb-4">What I Built</span>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">A live analytics layer over curriculum</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <p>
              I designed and built the whole system in Google Apps Script so it lived natively inside the
              school's existing Google Workspace — no new platform, no new login, no new vendor. The web
              app reads from the documentation tracker and surfaces it through purpose-built views:
            </p>
          </div>
          <ul class="space-y-3">
            {[
              ['Navigator', 'Browse and search every course and unit across ES, MS, and HS from one place.'],
              ['Standards view', 'A Visible-for-Learning heatmap plus gap analysis that shows which standards are covered, over-covered, or missing.'],
              ['HoD view', 'A department-level lens so Heads of Department can see and steward their own area.'],
              ['Curriculum Calendar', 'A Gantt-style timeline of when units are taught across the year.'],
              ['AI tab', 'Natural-language querying over the curriculum data for deeper, ad-hoc analysis.'],
            ].map(([title, desc]) => (
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-teal flex-shrink-0 mt-2"></span>
                <span class="text-gray-700"><strong class="text-navy">{title}.</strong> {desc}</span>
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mt-6">
            The system was in real, active use months before any formal launch — a curriculum coach was
            already flagging live bugs in August 2025, well ahead of the June 2026 rollout to the full
            leadership team.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- IMPACT -->
        <div>
          <span class="tag mb-4">Impact &amp; Results</span>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">From a project to onboarding infrastructure</h2>
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-8">
            {[
              { value: '50+', label: 'Leaders deployed to', sub: '10 SLT + 40+ ILT members' },
              { value: '81%', label: 'School-wide completion', sub: '849 units documented' },
              { value: '26', label: 'New teachers onboarded', sub: 'before arriving in Chennai' },
            ].map(({ value, label, sub }) => (
              <div class="text-center p-5 bg-gray-50 rounded-2xl">
                <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-amber mb-1">{value}</div>
                <div class="font-semibold text-navy text-sm">{label}</div>
                <div class="text-gray-500 text-xs mt-1">{sub}</div>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              The dashboard was deployed to 10 Senior Leadership Team members and 40+ Instructional
              Leadership Team members. But the clearest signal of impact came from how the underlying
              Shared Drive curriculum structure got used: in May 2026, the school director sent it to
              <strong class="text-navy">26 incoming 2026–27 teachers</strong> as the very first
              onboarding resource they received — before they had even arrived.
            </p>
          </div>
          <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-teal pl-5 my-8 text-gray-700 italic">
            "This is phenomenal work throughout this year that has provided extensive insight into our program."
            <footer class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-gray-500 not-italic">— Gretchen Galaty, High School Teacher</footer>
          </blockquote>
          <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-amber pl-5 my-8 text-gray-700 italic">
            "Over the past year, we have been working to move all of our curriculum documentation into a
            shared Google Drive structure to create greater consistency, accessibility, and alignment
            across the school."
            <footer class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-gray-500 not-italic">— Joel Bevans, Director, in the onboarding email sent to 26 incoming teachers</footer>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <!-- LESSONS -->
        <div>
          <span class="tag mb-4">Lessons Learned</span>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">What I'd carry forward</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-4">
            {[
              ['Build where people already are.', 'Living inside Google Workspace — no new platform — removed every adoption barrier. The best tool is one nobody has to be convinced to log into.'],
              ['Ship before you launch.', 'Having a curriculum coach catch real bugs in August, ten months before the formal rollout, meant the June launch landed on something already battle-tested.'],
              ['Make knowledge visible and it becomes infrastructure.', 'The moment curriculum became searchable and complete, it stopped being a documentation chore and became the thing a director hands new hires on day zero.'],
            ].map(([title, desc]) => (
              <li class="card">
                <p class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">{title}</p>
                <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">{desc}</p>
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </div>

      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <section class="py-16 bg-navy text-white">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 md:px-8 text-center">
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold mb-5">Curious what a curriculum dashboard could look like for your school?</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
          <a href="/work" class="btn-secondary border-white/40 text-white hover:bg-white hover:text-teal">More Case Studies</a>
          <a href="/work-with-me#contact" class="btn-amber">Let's Talk</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>
